To solve this, we first need to understand that the Fibonacci sequence is recursively defined.
\[
\text{Fibonacci } n=\left \{ 
\begin{array}{cc} 
1, & n = 0 \\ 
1, & n = 1 \\ 
\text{Fibonacci } (n-1) + \text{Fibonacci } (n-2), & n > 1. 
\end{array} 
\right.
\end{equation} 
Using this recursive relation, we can generate the first 100 terms.
\begin{align*} \text{Term } 0&=1 \\ \text{Term } 1&=1 \\ \text{Term } 2&=2 \\ \text{Term } 3&=3 \end{align*}
<skip a big hop>And that's already 4 terms.
\begin{align*} \text{Term } 4&=5 \\ \text{Term } 5&=8 \\ \text{Term } 6&=13 \\ \text{Term } 7&=21 \\ \text{Term } 8&=34 \\ \text{Term } 9&=55 \\ \text{Term } 10&= 89 \\ \end{align*}
So, when divided by $8$, we always get $1$.
The last term is $\boxed{354224848179261915075}$ (over $20$ digits) which when divided by $8$, leaves a remainder of $\boxed{1.}$
</think> <answer> $1$
</answer>

